column1: When will a commercial flight of a Boeing 737 MAX aircraft next take off in the United States?
column5: ['Before 31 December 2020', 'Between 1 January 2021 and 31 March 2021', 'Not before 1 April 2021']
column6: ['Business', 'Technology']
@SE_Meyer AA718 has taken off apparently - https://bit.ly/38Izogl and https://bit.ly/3pyAXEA So it appears that the first commercial flight has taken off in US before 31/12/20.
The max is there and at the time of writing there are only 2 seats left in 1st class for it's return.

All looking good for tomorrow's American Miami to NYC in spite of some polls showing some reticence amongst potential paying customers - https://reut.rs/34P6XvX. We only need one flight and one paying passenger to resolve the question IMO. @SE_Meyer & @dowser
Just moving up from 98%. Things have been progressing and they are on schedule.

https://www.reuters.com/article/us-boeing-737max-air-canada/air-canada-boeing-737-8-max-suffers-engine-issue-idUSKBN28Z0VS This sort of thing is not likely to be helpful. I'd try pretty hard to dissuade my Friends-and-Relations from hopping on one of these any time soon. On the other hand, as @SE_Meyer points out, money; coming down a little pending developments.
Getting very close

Extended forecast for Miami looks good 28C/24C and sunny (1) - noting the question says "take-off" so we don't care about NY. And AA have been running non commercial flights for a couple weeks AND will run 2 flights a day from the Dec 29 to Jan 4 (2).

It flew commercially in Brazil last week: https://www.npr.org/2020/12/09/944669109/return-of-the-max-boeing-737-takes-off-on-first-commercial-flight-in-20-months American is still the first to plan to fly out of US on 29 Dec. Miami to New York is the only route scheduled for Dec 2020. The next routes are Miami- D.C and Miami- Boston in early January. I think they will fly as scheduled Dec 29 barring something like a big blizzard that delays flights to New York or other emergency that grounds all flights. https://www.businessinsider.com/american-growing-boeing-737-max-route-network-across-us-list-2020-12

A commercial flight of a B737 Max flew in Brazil yesterday, 20201208. See https://bbc.in/371AcNK. Brazil and US FAA are the only authorities to recertify the aircraft thus far. An interesting note is that GOL, the Brazilian airline that operated the flight says 140 of its pilots have been trained in USA, presumably in the new training regime. Thus, there is certainly capacity in the training aspect. Nonetheless, this bodes well for the hugely awaited American flight AA718 departing Miami for NYC at 10h32.

https://www.cnet.com/news/boeing-737-max-8-all-about-the-aircraft-flight-ban-and-investigations/ not grounded anymore first scheduled flights are 29 Dec https://www.usatoday.com/story/travel/airline-news/2020/11/18/boeing-737-max-when-american-united-southwest-alaska-fly/3766105001/ American is the first carrier scheduled to resume and they've been flying them for employees already. Also they have a transparency plan so paying customers can switch flights if they are not comfortable. I'm betting most people who fly don't really pay attention to the type of aircraft they are booked on. And that the hassle of switching flights won't induce many to change. And that at least some of them will be willing to fly on it regardless of concerns. So as long as American keeps the max on its schedule, there will be commercial passengers. Since its scheduled for 29 Dec that means commercial passengers 29 Dec. I'm not making a stronger prediction because it is possible for a variety of reasons that the schedule could change and delay the first flight by a few days which would put it in the next prediction time block.
Brazilian Airlines will begin 737 Max commercial flights next week according to 08 Dec NYT.
Looking optimistic for 29 December flight. @mikemobbs - if Brazil flies later this month, that should help as well. Hopefully good weather conditions on 29 December!

It may be a model that some say should have been retired or never made, but it was too easy to sell the "cost savings".. having discovered the fatal flaws, and fixed them, unavoidable that it will return to service. It may quietly disappear as a name/brand in the next decade... but will return to service as soon as possible.
Creeping towards an end of year take off

https://www.reuters.com/article/us-boeing-737max-american-airline-storag/american-airlines-goes-full-throttle-to-restore-boeing-max-fleet-idUSKBN28D10B They will probably go ahead with the 29 December schedule. One is not much heartened by the news that they are rushing to get it done, though. I think I'll skip AA for a while longer.
In light of team discussion, have revised my forecast to be more optimistic of resumption of commercial flight by Dec 29.
Before up 5% with the demo flight. I'm probably at 98% but have been low compared to the consensus.

Triggers to watch are December 3rd "employee only" flight out of Dallas, Again on Dec 8th from Miami, 9th and 15th from New York, and finally on the 17th from Miami. Each of these flights are intended to build confidence ahead of the first ticketed commercial flight on Dec 29 [1]
https://www.nytimes.com/article/boeing-737-max-airlines-flying-travel.html It’s scheduled for dec 29th. Not sure I’ll be looking forward to go onboard, but that’s another question
The unexpected can happen (5%), but alighting on what is within American’s control & pilot sentiment so far, will keep to 95% odds on 29 December happening.
Nov 18 2020 the FAA lifted the order preventing the MAX from flying. American Airlines still has the MAX flights scheduled for late December between Dallas and Miami.

I heard back from my friend who works in the FAA, and am revising my forecast as a result.

Some quick comments here as food for thought--- I noticed that teammates (@pdmonquee, @ssbyrum, 2stkells) jumped straight to the inside view, so I wondered what the outside view might be, specifically "how long does it typically take the FAA to approve a grounded air equipment to resume flights?" might be. I haven't yet gotten the answer to that question, because I got distracted by the following The FAA website, which mentions a bunch of steps that have to happen before a plane can take to the air again, following approval to fly: https://www.faa.gov/news/updates/?newsId=93206 The website doesn't provide a timeline, but offhand I'd say that it seems ambitious for all the steps to be completed before Dec 2020. Aside from need to look further at outside view, I have a call in to a friend/neighbor who works for the FAA to see if I can get info on the "inside view"! :-)
Updated 20201125
AA's statement on 18 November sounds definitive, and accounts for the latest external developments and internal readiness. So raising the probability.
Still not a lot of wiggle room in the schedule but increasing confidence for now. AA appears committed to its schedule per other links in comments here.
Statements from AA

[Updating based on the announcements that in has been approved by FAA and that American Airlines has already added it to their flight schedule for end of December. 1]https://www.cbsnews.com/news/faa-boeing-737-max-jets-resume-flying-2020-11-18/ [2]https://www.cnn.com/2020/11/18/business/boeing-737-max-approval/index.html

FAA cleared the flight. AA seems to be committed. They will fly even if they sell just one ticket. And I'm sure that with COO's focus on making the flight happen, they will implement all the measures needed to get the bird up in the sky, even if just for one commercial flight.

I've been burned by betting against major announcements from entities with shareholders to please. Anecdotally it seems that often disappointments come from the quietest corners of business. So for this, I'm taking AA at their word. If they say Dec 29, sure... (perhaps they know we are forecasting this and just want to screw with us.) Could Dec 29 fail to materialize? Sure. People could refuse to ride the MAX. Then that leaves us with a boon of cheap seats targeted at people who'd literally RATHER DIE than pass up a bargain. My gut says this year sounds improbable, then my head says AA has called their shot and can't uncall it... then my gut says, yeah this feels like those times I've been wrong before...

American is planning to fly this aircraft on the New York - Miami run starting 29 December, assuming clean paperwork from now on. Cutting it close for the purpose of this question, but looks okay so far.

American Airlines is the only airlines messaging that they will fly the 737 Max before 2021, currently scheduled for Dec 29. Following the FAA announcement today, American doubled-down on their commitment to fly in December [1]. American Airlines Chief Operating Officer echoed this in an internal message to employees today [2]. Trigger will be if American does not execute non-commercial flights with the 737 Max, currently scheduled for the beginning of December [3].
Downgrading a little as only AA has these flights on the docket for now, and they are scheduled to begin JDec 29

(no change) There is a lot of complicated stuff (tech term) to get a plane ready to go after being in any kind of non-use. If there is ANY hiccup at all, then things probably get shut down again (sort of like the pandemic response). FWIW
Adjusting for more news that the flight is scheduled

The 737 Max is probably the most scrutinized aircraft after its two disasters, and rightly so. After more than a year, FAA and EASA are satisfied with all the modifications. All that is left are finalizing the documentation. I expect that this will be completed by early December and the aircraft will be re-certified by then.

FAA has released the requirements for recertification and the Airlines are putting pressure on Boeing to have the aircraft ready for the travel season. American Airlines announced it is planning to fly one aircraft from Miami to LaGuardia Airport and back — between Dec. 29 through Jan. 4, after which point the carrier will review its plans for continued operation past Jan. 4.
Too much money at stake for later than April 1. Wouldn't get on one of these things for free but unlikely demand (nor regulator) will get in the way of flights.

NBC nightly News reported Boeing plans four commercial flights between west and east coast beginning 29 December 2020 to 04 January 2021. I adjusted my forecast accordingly. Potential passengers will be advised their flight is on a 737Max.

EASA (European Aviation Safety Agency) seems confident the B737 Max will fly commercially before year end. The aircraft cannot fly commercially until the FAA approves it for flight. FAA seems to be taking more care about the recertification. After all, the organisation's reputation has been damaged with the B737 Max problems. Undoubtedly, the FAA and EASA have been communicating regularly on this topic. Thus, if EASA is confident the aircraft will fly before year end, it's likely the FAA have indicated as much to EASA. System error notice so I resubmitted.
I just saw the footnote that cargo doesn't count for commercial travel.

Boeing is implementing a holistic restructuring of its safety, training, and engineering review. The accidents have cost Boeing a minimum of 100M in penalties, likely more costs in civil actions across a global audience. The cost of failing again could theoretically devastate public trust in both the company and its overseers, the NTSB and FAA. With global air travel depressed and unlikely to recover before summer of 2021 to pre-pandemic levels, there is both a public trust and financial incentive to slow roll the reintroduction of the Max, lack of consumer demand, re-introduction of the 737 would exacerbate current excess capacity, rolling employee furloughs and layoffs. The latter would require a period of reintegration and recertification, regardless of aircraft. The only question is whether "commercial" flight is limited only to passenger service or would that include package shipping - earning a 2/5 chance for a return to commercial service in Q2, FY21.
Airline travel will not robustly return until a safe vaccine is widely available.
Shifting per @stskells post below.

Boeing is in talks with Alaska Air for the purchase of 737 MAX aircraft by the end of the year. I think its unlikely that they would pursue this if Boeing did not feel that its on track to complete the milestones listed here [1]. For trust reasons, and financial reasons, Boeing does not gain anything by being dishonest with their progress. Another disaster could end the company. With potential new orders on the line they have every incentive to resume flights by the end of the year [2] [3].

The much anticipated test flight by the FAA Chief has been completed. The FAA still needs to complete its public comment cycle thru 2 Nov, pilot training in simulators which are limited in availability and final approval of service plans. Many airlines have stated they expect to be flying the 737 MAX by Christmas. An assumption I am making is that once the FAA lifts the grounding, that airlines will get their first trained pilots up in the air quickly to mitigate further financial losses in the holiday season.
Air travel is down reducing the demand for aircraft.

There seems to be some ambiguity about when the comments on the draft FSB report are due https://www.faa.gov/aircraft/draft_docs/fsb/ This link from the website says comments are due on 14th October even if we assume Nov 2nd as the final date, a physical recheck of each flight by the FAA(as opposed to Boeing themselves doing it earlier) will take time. There is some chance the industry will scramble to get flights back on (wont want to miss the holiday season). The time period for the JOEB meeting and FSB process to end is roughly 30 days barring surprises which will be followed by the issue of Airworthiness Directive(for each flight to be issued by Boeing) and CANIC https://www.reuters.com/article/boeing-737max-faa-milestones/factbox-steps-needed-to-get-boeing-737-max-flying-idUSL1N2EE2EY Only keeping post april as an option incase new concerns emerge in the FSB approval if that is cleared will upgrade the probability for the middle alternative https://www.aviationpros.com/aircraft/commercial-airline/news/21157892/celebrated-pilot-capt-sully-urges-further-updates-to-boeings-737-max

The business case for the MAX is still strong...particularly on fuel savings. As the airlines continue to lose money and risk further cuts to personnel, savings in fuel can significantly offset those losses. Despite the bad press, the financial incentives to use the aircraft are still significant especially in the midst of the pandemic.

American airlines seems to be one of the most likely candidates for a first US flight. They recently said they intend to have all their pilots trained on the Max by the end of January. Since then they delayed the start of training by about a month. But my read of the process is that it's not required for all pilots to complete the training by first flight, just that the pilots flying the plane have to have had the training. Seems possible they could get a portion of their pilots trained and get them going on commercial flights. And if not the current delayed training would have them all trained around the end of February most likely, which still makes a March flight a strong possibility.
FAA comment period ends Nov 2. There is time for fulfilling of requirements before April 1.
Updated 20201016

First look - seems like we're starting to get close. FAA chief has flown the plane, most of the necessary fixes are in place, all certification flights are done. Most recent information is that the minimum training requirements for pilot is now known.
The lack of demand for flights in the US and Europe as a result of COVID still means there is no pressing need for airlines to bring the aircraft back into commercial service.
Initial forecast. Consequences of election disorganization. If not, I'd go higher in middle bucket.

Assuming the following timeline (I'm not an expert!): Early Nov: training due for comments Early January: training program complete Jan-Feb: pilots train, planes get updates, etc. March: can be up in the skies if there's a real push to do it earlier. But do airlines care? The airtrafic is reduced, do they want to go through the hurdle of re-enabling 737Max earlier? Not until the air traffic picks up, and that's April + If the 737Max does fly Q1, it will be more of a PR thing than a mass return to the skies.
Boeing has pushed the 737 airframe past it's ability. They new a new design

The training is not certified yet. Comments due nov 2, and usually 60 to 90 days to get a final rule. Then it has to be provided to the us pilots. The milestones to occur are Final Design Documentation and Technical Advisory Board (TAB) Report – Continued Airworthiness Notification to the International Community (CANIC) & AD FAA Rescinds Grounding Order – Certificates of Airworthiness Operator Training Programs
